            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Phlabianos (Flavianus), worthy and blameless, lived for 37 years, 3 months, 10 days.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#SA">
                <p>Flaviano, degno e innocente, visse 37 anni, 3 mesi, 10 giorni.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>According to Paolo Orsi, the urn still contained the deceased’s ashes when it was discovered, and
                    traces of gilding were still visible on some of the letters and the capital of one of the relief
                    columns. The use of the name Flavianus suggests a date after the beginning of the Flavian dynasty
                    (beginning with Vespasian, 69 AD), but Flavianus’ status as slave, freedman, or free remains
                    uncertain. The use of architectural elements in the form of the chest and a tabula ansata to frame
                    the inscription are typical features of ash chests of this period.</p>
            </div>
